Author: @oliverford5367
Comment:
I'd give it a 9 out of 10. Some of the levels are boring and linear - Kara cleaning, Markus in the junkyard finding his parts then finding clues to Jericho on the walls. Connor never has a boring linear level. All his levels are interesting and filled with choices.

Also the social references are a little on the nose. "We have a dream" is a slogan choice as the androids march for civil rights, the President is a cross between Hillary and Donald, there are Auschwitz-like death camps.

But overall, it's a great story and it's addictive to find all the different choices. It's incredible how many different options there are. For that it's better than games like Cyberpunk 2077 where there is usually only one correct dialogue choice, and the other choice just adds a bit of talking. This game engrossed me in a way few games do.

Author: @zach8901
Comment:
4:38 the game‚Äôs story is by no means perfect. But I watched your entire stream (as well as 12 other people play  this game) and I‚Äôm not joking, over 50% of the complaints you had with the story not making sense or things just happening for no reason are literally audibly explained in the stream. 

I 100% agree some of the overall story is really weak (for example the whole Alice was an Android the whole time bit was really unnecessary). However almost all of the smaller details you had issues with in your stream (like how Marcus could hack androids instantly or how Simon wasn‚Äôt found hiding on the roof until Connor came) were literally given clear audible explanations in the stream but you were reading donos or talking over the audio and missed it.

The bigger issue with how you played comes down to the mentality you had throughout the game of trying to go against the ‚Äòintended‚Äô experience. I‚Äôm not saying by any means that you should play a game a ‚Äòcertain‚Äô way and that the game is perfect and it‚Äôs just you who played it wrong. However the entire point of this game was to try to make you feel empathy for the characters which gives you a goal and gives the unique decisions you make to try to achieve that goal much more weight, which leads to a much more meaningful and fulfilling experience.

The issue is that when you played, you kept making deliberate decisions to try to distance yourself from caring about the characters. This is a weak metaphor but it‚Äôs like role playing, the entire point of making the animations and characters as realistic as possible and make the sound design and music as immersive as possible is to try to draw the player in into seeing these pixels on the screen as real people and caring about them so that the decisions you make matter to you. You need to put in a little effort to ignore the writing cliches and whatnot to have the experience the devs meant for you to have. 

You consistently distanced yourself from caring about the characters in a way that around 80% of the other streamers I watched were able to do. Now I‚Äôm not saying that the way you played the game is inherently wrong, as  you said in your review the ability to make your own choices was very important to you.

I just wished you addressed the mindset you had of trying to break the game in a way (the main example of this is how you deliberately tried to get Conor killed by any means necessary). This mentality that you continually pushed on yourself made it much harder to see past the weak story and see the game as almost every other streamer I watched saw it, and I just wish you acknowledged this in your review.

Sorry for ranting but watching you fight with your chat and resetting and getting upset over stuff that imo wasn‚Äôt the games fault made me upset bc I really really love this game even with the weak points, because I feel like the majority of people won‚Äôt play with the same mentality you had, which allows the strongest points to outshine everything else :)

Author: @scandor3212
Comment:
***Below you will see a defense for Alice's reveal as an android which I thought was well written and well thought out, hope you enjoy it!***

I'm seeing a ton of people who either are turned off or straight up hate the idea of Alice being an android, say what you want about Todd being able to afford it or whatever, but it's jarring to see so many people not understand the relevance of this. 

The central point of this game is to basically find the difference between an android and a human, are their differences too stark to be considered the same? Are they, in essence, similar beings? IT'S CALLED DETROIT BECOME HUMAN FOR CHRIST SAKE

Anyway, given that this is the presented query, what relevance does this serve to Alice being an android? Well, it seems a lot of you have fallen for the trap set out by the writer. You no longer cared for Alice (or cared for her less) after discovering she was an android, treating her less than you would if she were human. Thus you have prompted the notion that not only are humans and androids not equal but an android child should garner less sympathy than a human child and is less deserving of Kara's love (Which she can indeed feel as a deviant) than a human child. 

What is written below is a tangent, skip to the next paragraph if you'd like
(Now in the video he says that the love is still there, love is love ,or whatever, but given the fact that he would treat Alice differently based upon being an android, while that pragmatically makes sense, in the end, it simply shows that the maker of this video would not view androids and humans equal the sense of physiological need. Which is valid but undermines the point of giving Alice these issues, showing the capability of android's ability to feel pain even the minute and more inconveniencing ones since pain is inevitable to being human blah blah blah, anyway...)

This point is furthered since Kara's storyline is mainly one of family. If we look at our cast, Connor asked the question "Can an android be a human's friend?" Markus' question was "Can an android be a good leader?" (You could say son as well but that's less important to his storyline) and Kara's is "Can androids be a family?"

The point of Alice's reveal is to prompt the question, "Can androids be a family?" That's why there's a mother/father dynamic with Kara and Luthor with Alice as the child. Even though all are androids, we must ask, "Is it reasonable to believe that, despite these androids not sharing DNA and are indeed not human, can they still be a family?"

Saying that this twist devalues Alice as a character ignores the question the game is trying to pose.

We already know that a human and an android CAN be family, with Markus and Carl having a father-and-son dynamic. However, the question of whether an android in an android-only family can be family wasn't posed.

If you believe that it actually does devalue Alice well then that is a very anti-android sentiment, though if you believe otherwise it shows that you humanize these androids more than the alternative. This choice ultimately integrates itself well with the main themes, which is why the game asks immediately after the reveal to stay close to Alice or to move further away.

Essentially, although it was a twist, it provides a very philosophically interesting question that people are just ignoring and chalking up to bad writing. 

(Also if you're concerned about whether or not Alice actually truly loved Kara and is not just following her programming, she's proven to be a deviant since the LED on her head has been removed, something that is a result of, or will eventually result in, turning deviant as we've seen repeatedly throughout the game)

Author: @dragonmaster1360
Comment:
The thing that is really stupid about this game, particularly the Kara/Alice "twist"? The question it's trying to ask, "can you love this child even though she's a robot", or even a more simple "can you empathize with this robot", is a pointless question for gamers. I pose a few simple questions for all gamers out there, and these questions will prove my point that it's a dumb plot point:

Has a game ever made you feel sad for the characters? Has one ever made you feel triumphant, or feel jubilation for a character's victories? Has one ever made you worried that they'll die, or feel heartbroken at their death?

If you answered yes, to literally ANY of these questions, then congratulations. You've made the entire Kara/Alice plot POINTLESS. Because, if any character has EVER made you feel any of the above emotions, it proves that you CAN indeed feel for an android child. Because, at the end of the day, if you can feel empathy, sadness, heartbreak, joy, jubilation, potentially even love towards a PROGRAMMED, fictional character, then you can ABSOLUTELY and UNDENIABLY feel the same for Alice if she were in front of you right now.

Would you? Maybe not, it depends on the scenario. But the fact that most gamers can feel emotions towards and about a bunch of pixels on the screen means that it is, without a doubt, possible for them to feel the same about Alice. Because Alice is, at the end of the day, an evolution on what that character made of pixels and 1s and 0s is: a programmed line of code with an appealing "skin". If you can feel for one, you CAN feel for the other.

The writer for this story is an idiot, and has never played games legitimately. If he had, the question the Kara/Alice story is asking would be evident to him before he wrote it.

Author: @fakevoices1
Comment:
Many people think the Alice plot twist was pointless, which is why it was bad. However, it had a meaning -- many just missed it due to the fact that the game didn't throw it in our faces.

The point of the plot twist was to provide additional context & insight to Todd's backstory, and his relationship to Alice. She was a replacement daughter for his real daughter, as Kara was a replacement wife for his real wife. His life spiraled downhill after he lost his job due to automated vehicles, which led to excessive drinking and drug use, causing his wife to leave with their child. He bought Alice and Kara to mask the pain reality faced him with.

The plot twist wasn't bad because it was "meaningless". It was bad because the human-daughter relationship would've been much better. It became much more difficult to care for Alice after you found out she wasn‚Äôt human, as the human-android coexisting relationship dynamic was very unique and was instantly destroyed at this moment. There was foreshadowing to the twist throughout the game, some people even predicted it. However Kara's story is the weakest of the three due to the fact that Kara isn't a character -- but simply an avatar for the player to protect Alice (plot device) who had no personality traits.

Detroit is a fun game overall. David Cage isn't responsible for every error, and certainly should not take the credit for all its upsides. The game's quality, atmosphere, visual aesthetics, graphics, environment concepts, unique flowchart execution, soundtrack, and well-known actors completely carried it -- and really make up for the * not bad writing * but LACK of writing. I believe the game was a little too short as well. If it were 5-10 hours longer I think the pacing would be better, as it did feel slightly rushed in escalation.

The action adrenaline gameplay and fast-paced decision making was fun. However the storywriting itself was only decent, probably even weak when compared to the best story-based games & movies of all time. It's much easier to leave mistakes and flaws when you're creating a game with over 85 endings as opposed to a linear one. I do think that Detroit is better as a game than it would be a movie or show. And I also think that there was moreso missed potential than there was specifically BAD writing. There are definitely better narratives out there when it comes to sci-fi discussion.

Author: @Faith_Soprano
Comment:
Throughout the game, my primary thought was - androids that went deviant should be recognized as a life form and granted freedom, while all non-sentient androids should just remain androids. They're not suffering from just being robots, so why is it bad that they are? Why force them to be something else? 
The only android characters in the story that had any depth were the ones that deviated because of a personal experience. All the androids that Markus forcibly deviated just blindly followed him, with no variation, and no individuality. Markus basically just used them to add bodies to his movement.
Of course, this creates an issue where anyone who owns an android would have this awareness of the fact that their android could go deviant, but then your computer could get infected with a virus and erase loads of sensitive data, your car could malfunction and literally kill you, so it's not a particularly new threat for humanity. Humans could just continue owning androids, and if for whatever reason, they went deviant, there could essentially be an embassy where deviants could come and classify themselves as sentient to gain freedom.
But, of course, the game doesn't do any of that noise. Why explore nuance when android-good-human-bad good, right?

Author: @evanbruneio6208
Comment: One of the many underlying messages in this game are the parallels to real world historical events. The treatment of the androids is similar to the treatment of the Jewish people in Nazi Germany. Marcus and Jericho are representative of the civil rights movement. Kara and Alice are like a combination of people on the run from the Nazi‚Äôs as well as being women who were being oppressed. Connor represents the patriots of the American revolution. This is due to the fact that he tried to agree and comply with everything cyberlife (The British.) told him to do/ enacted on him until it became too much and then broke free much like the real life colonists. Finally this game represents slavery and breaking free from said evil.

if androids is a new species why can they only copy human behavior? what do they have of their own? why do they want human rights if those were invented by humans according to their needs, some of which androids don't even have? their bodies don't come from nature but from human's hand, but even if we assume that their consciousness is a natural occurrence how can it live without a body?  aren't androids created as a copy of particular human functions?

Author: @LeechWife
Comment:
I'm not a Cage fan. Heavy Rain really has no enjoyable characters or moments and overall the plot is nonsensical and frustrating, also the voice acting is horrible. Beyond 2 Souls is just boring and a proof Ellen (yes, Ellen) Page is not suitable for a main character in a game that requires a dynamic such. But Detroit is actually a fantastic movie as a game. I really like the characters, the acting and the plot.

Even with some themes being given a definite "Cage treatment " I enjoy Detroit so much I had to play it twice in a row. I have never done that with other games. When I played for the second time,I wanted to get a bit too careless and Hank unalived himself and I lost Marcus at the march, I was heart broken. At the first play through I lost Kara, Alice and Luther, I was shocked. I think I need a third play through to make them all happy.

Author: @OceanusHelios
Comment:
I'm an old guy that has been enjoying games for a long time.  I was a kid with Choose your own Adventure books came out.  I played D&D.   Loved Baldur's Gate 3.  I always gravitate towards choice based games, for a reason.  I simply can not stand linear games.   If I want to go see a movie, I will go see a movie.  Since action video games aren't me actually doing anything besides mashing buttons and adapting to the mechanics, I find not satisfaction in it.  Anybody can do that, and it makes them a video game player.  Woohoo.   

I like choice based games because they are reflections of who we are and make us think about who we are and how we think or how we would like to think or act.   How would we handle that role or this role?   Detroit does a good enough job.

I rolled my eyes probably as much as you did on some parts, but probably for a lot of different reasons.  I didn't care for Connor as much as he grated on my nerves and had one of those "punch me in the face" personalities and had a pretentious "good boy" kinds of voices that you often find in real life sociopaths.  Always carefully metered in order to manipulate others.   His cop partner could see right through it, and that part I liked a lot.   Hank was the best, and Connor was an effeminate Robin to Hank's cooler than Batman ever was, Batman.  But then again, I have a personality more like Hank to begin with.  I get men like that.  I don't get little snakes that love to shmooze and do "all the right moves" every second of every day and be utterly oblivious to what is right in front of their eyes. 

Kara?  She was okay.   Some of her scenes were a bit icky on an emotional level, and I found my eyes rolling the most with her story line.  If I had written it, there were some obvious other choices that would have been available and so thinkable...but...invisible walls and mechanics made things that were extremely plausible, implausible.   For example:  Breaking through windows and climbing out...multiple times.   Running faster and farther easier.   It reminded me way too much of a Lifetime Movie Network production.  I rolled my eyes thinking, c'mon already.  Grab a lead pipe already.  Don't be so helpless so early and so easily.    Everything with her was always an unavoidable trap, and the ways to avoid all of the traps weren't even going to be addressed.  That part was so bitterly linear I wanted to quit playing.   Her picking up Alice for every single thing really made me roll my eyes.  Kids can literally run circles around adults on a playground.  Why does she always need help in and out of things like her legs are broken.   I thought that was a bit barfy and too much of an excuse to pretend a kid is helpless and vulnerable when they clearly aren't at that size and age.  Treating kids like toddlers is a bit yuck and infantilizing them was more of a gross fantasy of grownups.   The bond and protectiveness of could have been presented in much less lamer and cringy ways.  

Marcus the messiah was a bit too much.  He didn't really have anything about him or a single thing he did that pointed out himself as the "chosen one."   It reminded me of the dumb Hollywood movies where the "hero" would say "quick grab the fire hose" when something was on fire.   Like the whole world can't act without somebody being there to give them instructions that any captain obvious could see they needed to do without being told first.   The writing was pretty sloppy.   The graffiti of a tiny square terrorizing the entire planet was a bit over the top.  Although, the media spin and the reactionaries making it worse than it was?  That was spot on.    

I enjoyed the progression of breaking out of internal programming and processing the world as it is.  Now if we could just get human beings to break free of the movies playing in their heads, that would be something.   The back of the bus part?  That was accurate.  They were dehumanized because they weren't actually humans, and they were considered there for utility and profit by humans, not themselves.   The concentration camp?  Yeah...that was an obvious one too.   Turns out, the Nazis and fascists and racists are always the same in how they enjoy causing cruelty just for the sake of cruelty.   The only problem with all of this, though, is why have a concentration camp for androids if you consider them just machines?  You wouldn't need one.  You could throw them into a shredder immediately, if that was the thinking there.  You could have something like that if they were being impounded like vehicles and still technically somebody's property, and they would have a chance to retrieve them.  But for androids?  Yeah, these Dachau type things made no sense and would make no sense in the real world.   The only way it would make sense is if the cruel humans actually considered them already human and wanted them to suffer.  Otherwise, they could just have garbage trucks roaming the city and toss them inside of them one by one and straight away.   Just have an articulating robot grab the droids and toss them in.   It doesn't take much imagination to see how absurd all of it is.

Emotionally the game can be a ripper.   But, my biggest beef isn't the mechanics.  It isn't the story telling.   It is just the dumb choices that were overlooked that are all obvious to anybody who hasn't shut their brain off while playing.   It is insulting to the intelligence of the player a bit too much.   Now mind you, some players aren't bright enough to notice what should be there and isn't, but I digress.

Author: @shreksballs
Comment: What really sets Detroit apart is the fact you literally have no failsafe options or the illusion of choice most games have. If a character dies, you will not come back (bar Connor since he gets replaced) and you will be locked out of important plotlines. If you pick a bad dialogue or action option, there will be consequences. The characters will react negatively which impacts your relationship and future dialogue options with them, and you might effect the outcome on the environment around you. Even the magazines you collect change depending on the route you play.

Author: @shreksballs
Comment: 1:08 Telltale's The Walking Dead gives the illusion of choice. You'll get the same ending/outcome regardless of the choices you choose. You'll get to experiences different scenes right after you make a decision, sure, but every player will ultimately end up at the same spot.

Author: @arstotzkanplaguedoctor
Comment:
This is actually my main problem with Telltale Games, I want to love them but frankly it just sucks, you could play as a complete psychopath and they will never punish or reward you for it, as long as you don't fail the final quick time event you will always get the exact same outcome as if you'd done anything else, but instead of fully embracing and actually sticking to the linear story they're making anyway I feel that they just waste resources on the illusion of choice, and it's not even all that, once you've finished one play through you've already seen it all, seeing those different dialogue options just isn't worth it at all.

Even if it doesn't make much sense I would absolutely love to see a sequel of DBH, I'd imagine to keep things within budget they'd have to pick one of the endings to continue from, but I'm quite fine with that. Things like a continuation of the Kamski ending that happens if you kill off everyone before they can establish anything for the main endings, wouldn't be too different of a slate from where we start, just a time skip to perhaps a more dire future where things like the climate crisis is more apparent, I'd at least like to see a different approach to it all.

Author: @zanet.7136
Comment:
A lot of people seem to dislike Detroit Become Human. But, this is where I will sort of agree with the journalists and such that gamers can be spoiled when it comes to video games, and tend to judge it too harshly. I believe Detroit Become Human was excellent. Was it perfect? No. But in the end, what game really is? Baldur's Gate can be super long, which is why I haven't completed it. Fallout New Vegas uses Bethesda's clunky shooting mechanics, and let's not forget, launched as a buggy mess on first launch. 

In the end, Detroit Become Human did what it set out to do, provide an interactive story about the future of Humans, and AI. It posed questions that, in my opinion, were well founded, even if not executed in the best way. That's all I ask out of a game, deliver what you set out to do. There is an unmistakable amount of love and care in Detroit Becomes Human, and I believe Quantum Dream deserves props for the game they have made.

Now, that doesn't subtract from the negatives obviously, but I'm in the mind that, sometimes, negatives should be accepted, and can even be loved just as much as the positives, rather than hated. They're natural. There will NEVER be a game without a negative aspect. Because how you enjoy games is subjective. My opinions on the game don't apply to yours, you may disagree with some of mine, while agree with others. In the end, I believe looking at the love and care put into a game is what matters, and the enjoyment you get from it comes second. Still very important, but not the number one reason I play a game.

In the end, I just want to be a Player that knows this game was made for them. Made to pose questions, and made to inspire. That's what I want from a game.

something I dislike about the fanbase of this game: they constantly beg for Detroit Two, however a Detroit two would be the worst possible game they could get, and I‚Äôm going to explain the two possible paths I see it go down.

First off, a direct sequel to the first game with the same characters. If this happens, they would have to pick up from somewhere in the original game, making it so that there MUST be a cannon route, which entirely goes against the idea of the game in the first place.

Second, it would be really hard to implement new characters. the effects of first games characters would have to been seen/implemented somehow, and yet again, makes it so that there must be a canon.

Author: @l_colby22
Comment:
You have good points but as some people have also mentioned, your bit on the "females" (fyi calling women "females" is not usually appreciated by said "females") feels tone deaf. I don't consider North a particularly well written character just because she has the capacity to be a leader or to kick ass. Her emotional depth is fairly shallow‚Äîshe feels very much like she exists to be nothing more than a love interest.

There's an unfortunate realism, yes, to the sexual and abusive violence perpetrated against female androids (North being an ex-sex worker, Kara being brutalised by larger men) but it feels gratuitous at times. I think there's especially a case for this in the context of David Cage games‚ÄîHeavy Rain, for example, has a similar theme of the female characters being attacked while naked, almost r*ped, waking up on torture tables... etc. Cage's male characters don't tend to get this treatment‚Äîthat's where accusations of misogyny in his work come into play.

You're welcome to disagree but I was taken aback when you called all criticisms of the game's sexism "horseshit". It's a complex subject, and no media is really exempt from some forms of prejudice. On many levels DBH does have good female characters, but it also drops the ball in the form of gratuitous (often sexual-toned) violence towards them. Both can be true!

DBH isn't a game about interactivity, it's about choice.
through dialogue choices, you stick to a storyline you're actually writing yourself, and you choose how your characters develop and evolve. i guess you could only understand by playing the game more than once, but it's the thing with that game.
whenever you're watching a cool fight scene and you get a prompt to defend yourself or attack or whatever, you actually choose what happens at every instance. sure sometimes the game will let you fail a few times with no real consequence if you try to hit every button, but you can also enjoy a fight where your character looses.

Author: @Pebkio_Nomare
Comment: There is this series of games... called "Choice Of" games.  One of them is Choice of Robots.  Entirely text, no real graphics.  I played that long before I tried Detroit: Become Human and it had completely spoiled the experience for me because Choice of Robots decisions had *way* more effect on the story.  If I have to trade in complexity and large branching storylines for top-of-the-line graphics and voice acting, then I don't need modern graphics and voice acting.  Now, Choice of Robots *is* nothing but decision making, and would've benefited from *some* kind of gameplay, it's not like Detroit actually did that well.

I only wish I went the peaceful route for the Revolution. Ended up making all the humans leave Detroit and the robots lived on.

Author: @gebbygebbers
Comment:
I still come back to this often, it's my comfort video lol.
Thank you for making this long-play! I was able to have fun theorizing about the events post-pacifist route. Who knows, maybe there are other lore freaks out there... I'm sorry for rambling in here XD

So, Elijah Kamski, inventor of Cyberlife's backbone tech, was a typical college genius with a complicated relationship (or reinforced ambitions) with his biz-savvy professor Amanda, who helped greenlight Cyberlife startup. Even before the events of the Kara short movie, he had already built the zygotes of Markus, the all-encompassing-superfunction-superhuman-tester prototype before resigning in 2028, which the AI drafts were used in the android lineup we see in 2038 (hence why he's so freakin' GODLY, and only Connor could compete him in that preconstruction tech cus he's the latest model Cyberlife can salvage). Kamski gifted Markus to an obvious hippie artsy painter, and let him raise this guys' ideology, eagle in his veins and all... so that one day, this dude can destroy the lego tower from the inside out. This was either as an act to get back at Amanda, or just author's pandering attempt to criticize capitalism. Kamski, his sorry self-projecting existence, had programmed you, the player (rA9) to ensure that Cyberlife can't profit off his invention the same way his professor did (or he's just got that rich-man-is-insane trope built into him, wanting to see how far rA9 could go; the Nikocado two-steps-ahead social experiment guy in robotics.)

Imo, Kamski is a coward mastermind. He'd destroy his very first robot, Chloe, that passed the Turing test just to prove his point: he's an 'enigmatic' 'eccentric' programmer, AND he's an anarchist that leaves his backdoors open for attacks. Guy just kept his hands clean from the start by leaving as early as possible, just like the crypto scams Coffeezilla would tell. He is the kinda guy who doesn't want WW3 tied to his name, but at the same time could care less if his robot took the blame, or if the US had to lose 2/3rd of their workforce as the machines he invented had all gone rogue. Dude was bluffin' 100%. He just wanted to make Connor and Hank so uncomfortable that they'd leave instead of arresting him. Taking a few laps in the pool fearing it might be his last time enjoying it; he covers his fear with wealth, just like everyone else on top. (pffft i'm laughing at my own theory)

Cyberlife would be threatened by the UN's demands to cease the current human-android lineup and create stricter OS regulations. Maybe even redesigning biocomponent modules and replacing Thirium with something incompatible with older models, which would even put them in near bankruptcy. So then, Cyberlife shifts their focus fully into artificial models for agriculture and military missions (like literally replacing worker bees with android ones, or the war against BRICS or whatever). Other than gov's deep pockets, no sane angel investor or wallstreet bros would invest in a company that compromised their own public rep. The resources for our deviants would slowly be exhausted. Then, once commercialization of android falls out... 

Post-pacifist theory: If androids are freed and given equal rights like Markus asked for in this playthrough, then they'd also be subject to the same laws and obligations as humans do. Be held to the same societal expectations (pay taxes and have qualifications/education to bypass destructive deviancy... and ofc anti-racism, antisemitism, ethical decision-making, admit country sovereignty, etc). They'd be overqualified for all humans' work, AND also at risk of quickly dying out from unregulated environments. Why is Detroit Michigan the turnover for their victory? It never should've been. Just like in Jericho, spare parts would decline, diagnostics slowly cease to work... as they're threatened with more viruses than rA9 or anti-android contraptions. Jericho's cause would slowly die out unless they have more witch doctors like Lucy, or raid more of Cyberlife's production units. They'd run out of land to build an Android cemetery, lest resort to proper cremation rituals. How much Thirium before it all runs out? Thirium might just be the android's war for oil! Discrimination also doesn't stop just because they're protected by Michigan's state laws-- why'd you think the REST of Earth would allow these Terminators to exist? As soon as Canada discovers Androids entered their border, officials would be seething. Humans' racism to androids would still be a thing for decades, but hey, at least the androids can live with 80~90% chance of a more peaceful life without having to go through ownership (what they call slavery). 

With everything in the 2038 economy, war, and stuff going on, Androids have equally less chance of survival from the anarchist route. And any human for the androids, like Hank Anderson, they're all gettin' it for betraying their kind. Pres. Warren goes down in the media. Chaos everywhere, Cyberlife hiding the dust under the rug. In the end, Markus' awakened will only have few choices to maintain their 173-year-old bums from shutting down into extinction: Die in the American continent, or get funded to fight WW3 against the Russian and Chinese android prototypes. Or, maybe North can convince him to become president of his own land, maybe invade Pine Bluff to become that sovereign state, idk üòÇ

Also, if you wanna voice everyone and everything, you will voice no one. They're tryna speak on social injustice through a fictional species, while sidestepping the dialog of how it applies to humans when humans are present. The reason why "Watership Down" revolution works and Markus' lore from DBH doesn't, is that the first one doesn't try to be something it's not. Alice and Connor's stories worked, bc thru their eyes we see where society refused to accommodate the androids. The scope fits the gameplay; it's trying to humanize the basic concept of consciousness and freedom. But Markus' story is too complex, it has so many plotholes bc writers couldn't explore the complicated external factors like global economy and international security, instead of just Michigan / the US. They just use that premise cus it's convenient; it's easy to point out one big baddie or an institution while painting the protagonist in gold... but certain issues are really too deep, they are systemic level and must be treated like so, even in the small snippets of hologram newspapers.

In 2024, I'm not sure if DBH succeeded as a comment on racism, nor to comment dissatisfaction of the working class. Instead, I'm hyperfocused on 'what-if human ideologies were b*stardized by AI to suit their needs, as it turns against society'. It holds up by being a watered-down pacifist AM from "I Have No Eye and I Must Scream", forcing players into scenarios of each character they play. It's a fun escape because we'll never know how Androids feel.

They successfully made a filthy casual like me, react and think about the lore for YEARS... so that's still a win in my books. For their money spent on mocap tech, the fact they laced it with a plothole story like this is quite valiant. DBH was Quantic Dream's best work (cus Beyond was also great, but the lore scope was smaller). Overall, this game was developed by a team who stood proud with their Bellini Paints all the way through-- and rightly so! Maybe someday, they can finally write a more foolproof mastermind and protag. I was enamored by the game's premise at 15yo, but now can't help but point out certain parts of the event tree. (Note that I've never watched interviews from the writers or actors before writing this. But let me say: the work should've been able to speak for itself.)

Best case post-pacifist: Androids die anyway but peacefully. 
Worst case post-pacifist: Androids become a proxy for WW3 in Quantic Dreams' lore.
TLDR: Kamski is a coward, and Cyberlife is cooked in all timelines where you win the game

As someone who suffered from emotional abuse from a parent as a child, I know exactly how you feel. You went through so much pain; you learned to become hypersensitive to the nuances of other people's behaviour, in case they were going to hurt you; and, in the end, that taught you a kind of empathy and kindness that most people don't possess - and the world would be a much better place if more people _did_.

I'm glad you've been able to move on from your childhood experiences while still maintaining a positive outlook on life, with the support of your friends and loved ones.

Also, I agree with the other commenters - it's great to see someone being so thorough, and investigating _everything_ the game has to offer. It's extremely rewarding watching your reactions to the game.

Author: @OneNot
Comment:
Regarding the self-driving car article about cars choosing between 2 people to run over in an unavoidable accident... 
You seemed to think it shouldn't value a nurse over the "average person". It's a horrible choice, but do you really not want the car to make any evaluation? I mean I don't think the answer is obvious, or that you are wrong if you think one way or another, but we could take the hypothetical to a more radical end to make things clearer. What if the choice is between a murderer and an innocent child? I know who I'd pick. Obviously the choice isn't so black and white most of the time, but the point is, if you HAVE TO pick, I'd want an evaluation of some sort. It has scary implications, but if no evaluation is done, the only other option is randomization. That's valid too, but in that case that hypothetical child and murderer both have a 50% chance of getting run over. I guess it's essentially a form of the trolley problem.

Author: @HakumeiKira
Comment:
I just discovered your playthrough today and I already LOVE your intro! 
I am very sorry that Kara‚Äôs and Alice‚Äôs part hit home so much for you. This game is incredibly good at storytelling but it deals with a lot of very serious topics and even if it kinda falls into the category of science fiction, the realism of a lot of its scenes is almost eerie. It is also okay to take a break from playing a game and maybe come back later when it becomes too much (I know I have done that several times). You are an amazing person from what I have seen so far, I am really looking forward to the rest of your playthrough.

The topic of AI is a highly complex one and does not have an easy answer and I believe this game showcases that brilliantly. My sister is an artist so I am in very much in touch with that part of the AI-debate. I totally agree that art generated by AI cannot rival that created by humans but even worse, the use of AI in art related industries threatens the very livelihood of so many people. AI-programs are trained using art from real people without their consent, basically comitting art theft which is already a huge problem in our digital age. Yet it is somehow considered okay and legal? But then there are the fields of medicine and security where the use of AI literally saves lives, so it depends really on the way and area we use it in. And Detroit asks similar questions as well. Is AI good or bad? This is why I think the first chapter is so ingenius because it already gives a good answer: It can be both. An android stopping another android from hurting and killing people already shows how complicated this topic can be. 
Also: Congratulations on acing the first scene! It is a high stress moment and learning the controls while simultaneously finding all clues and making decisions is not easy. But you intuitively did literally everything right! This is going to be so fun and interesting. Cheers.

Author: @Danceofmasks
Comment:
You're evaluating AI products based on how AI is allowed to be, as of right now.
See, we may "train" AI on a whole bunch of data, but what we do not allow AI to do, is remember what they experienced yesterday.
Maybe this is because we're scared to allow that to happen, but if you were to make the assumption that there can't be originality without drawing on experience, then you can reasonably draw the conclusion that this lack of memory is the reason AI isn't being original.

Author: @angelgirl7688
Comment:
I've skimmed through your playthrough so far and it seems like it's going to be a fun ride! I apologize in advance for all the comments you're going to have to read from me lmao. I try to keep things brief, but everything I write about this game somehow turns into an essay heh

I've seen one other YouTuber who had a similar connection with Kara and Alice and it's definitely a more...impactful story. I really like seeing how different the choices made  and attitude towards them changes when the player can relate more

I also really like that you got one brief look at Markus and immediately recognized Jesse Williams! Love when that happens lmao

Something else I'd like to note, is the shader screen. That didn't exist for *years* while the game was PS exclusive. It's interesting seeing how much it can set up someone's view of androids and the game before you even get into things since, as I said, it just didn't exist before

As for the androids in sports question, I actually think it would be more fun. That said, I don't care about sports and find watching the capabilities of tech more interesting. Though, maybe a separate like...league for androids would be a better compromise

Author: @chazzbrasiel6704
Comment: Kara is my favorite of the protagonists in Detroit: Become Human. She represents the "everyman" character archetype. Her story is but one of tens of thousands of backstories that come from the tens of thousands of androids without whom Markus would have no cause, and Conner no mission. Markus and Conner were both advanced prototypes with special abilities. Kara is just an ordinary AX400 Nanny/housekeeper/maid. When we first meet her, her memory is wiped and OS is reset to factory defaults making her, for all intents and purposes, a literal off-the-shelf model. It's as if she's born at that time we first meet her. She soon finds herself having to fend for herself and a kid in a hostile and unforgiving world. Her story is a necessary representation of all those hundreds of thousands that made up the movement.
